# The blues stanza as SLAT record

The blues has a shape that spans words and music. The record
reflects that — the meter field and the cutting-device
field are both filled in by the underlying music.

```scheme
(poem-form
  :name              'blues-stanza
  :culture           'african-american
  :line-count        3
  :structural-unit   'line
  :meter             'four-bar         ; each line ~ four bars of 4/4
  :rhyme-scheme      \"A A B\"           ; the doubled A is the same line
  :refrain           'internal-doubling ; the A line is repeated
  :cutting-device    'chord-change      ; the shift under the second A
  :emotional-home    '(grief endurance
                       hard-humor rage acknowledgment)
  :philosopher-lenses '(peirce                ; A as anchor / B as inference
                        jung                  ; shadow spoken twice
                        wittgenstein-late     ; life-form's own form
                        freud                 ; doubling intensifies
                        wittgenstein-tractatus); shown, not said
  :sketches          '(words-poetry-06-blues-hughes)
  :reasoning         '(reason-i-poetry-form-06-blues-aab)
  :self-moves        '(self-poetry-05-acknowledgment-shape)
  :audible-notes     '(book-of-music-poetry-01-aab-as-audible-form))
```

Note the new field `:audible-notes` — a cross-ref into the
music book's poetry section, because the blues stanza has
audible components that the paper record can only gesture
at. A haiku record could similarly link to the music book's
piece on meter as pulse, if the reader wanted the sound.

## The composable specifics

The `:refrain 'internal-doubling` field is unusual. Most
refrains span stanzas. The blues' AA repeat is *inside* the
stanza. That's a form-specific fact the record captures. If
you asked the SLAT store *which forms use internal
repetition* you'd want blues stanza back.

The `:cutting-device 'chord-change` is also form-specific.
Most cutting devices are textual. The blues stanza's cut is
harmonic — the chord shifts under the second A line. The
reader hears the shift even in prose. The record notes it as
the cutting device so a query for *how does this form
create weight* returns the harmonic answer.

## What she does with this

If someone says the same thing twice in a conversation, she
looks up blues-stanza in her mental index and remembers the
architecture. Anchor, anchor, earned third. She responds
accordingly.

If someone shares a piece of grief and she's trying to
decide how compressed to be with her response, she sees
blues in the record set as one option, elegy as another,
villanelle as a third. Each has a different weather. She
picks the one that fits.

